 {"id":"bd-3q7e","title":"PriorityScheduler: replace O(n) insert with heap","description":"# Performance: Replace O(n) Insert with Binary Heap

## Location
`src/runtime/scheduler/priority.rs:27-43`

## Current Implementation

```rust
fn insert_by_priority(lane: &mut VecDeque<SchedulerEntry>, entry: SchedulerEntry) {
    let pos = lane
        .iter()
        .position(|e| entry.priority > e.priority)
        .unwrap_or(lane.len());
    lane.insert(pos, entry);  // O(n) insertion
}
```

## Problem

- Linear scan to find insertion position: O(n)
- VecDeque::insert at arbitrary position: O(n)
- Total: O(n) per schedule operation
- With 10,000 pending tasks, each schedule costs 10,000 comparisons

## Proposed Solution

Replace VecDeque with BinaryHeap:

```rust
use std::collections::BinaryHeap;
use std::cmp::{Ordering, Reverse};

#[derive(Eq, PartialEq)]
struct SchedulerEntry {
    task: TaskId,
    priority: u8,
    generation: u64,  // For FIFO within priority
}

impl Ord for SchedulerEntry {
    fn cmp(&self, other: &Self) -> Ordering {
        // Higher priority first, then earlier generation (FIFO)
        self.priority.cmp(&other.priority)
            .then_with(|| other.generation.cmp(&self.generation))
    }
}

struct PriorityScheduler {
    ready_heap: BinaryHeap<SchedulerEntry>,
    generation: u64,
}

impl PriorityScheduler {
    fn schedule(&mut self, task: TaskId, priority: u8) {
        self.generation += 1;
        self.ready_heap.push(SchedulerEntry {
            task,
            priority,
            generation: self.generation,
        });
        // O(log n) insertion
    }

    fn pop(&mut self) -> Option<TaskId> {
        self.ready_heap.pop().map(|e| e.task)
        // O(log n) removal
    }
}
```

## Complexity Improvement

| Operation | VecDeque | BinaryHeap |
|-----------|----------|------------|
| Insert    | O(n)     | O(log n)   |
| Pop       | O(1)     | O(log n)   |
| Peek      | O(1)     | O(1)       |

For n=10,000: 10,000 → 13 comparisons per insert

## Trade-offs

**Pros:**
- Dramatic improvement for large queues
- Standard library implementation (well-tested)
- Generation counter preserves FIFO within priority

**Cons:**
- Pop is now O(log n) instead of O(1)
- Slightly higher memory overhead
- Can't iterate in order without sorting

## Testing Strategy

1. Benchmark current vs heap implementation
2. Verify FIFO ordering preserved within priority
3. Stress test with 100,000+ tasks
4. Memory usage comparison

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] BinaryHeap implementation
- [ ] FIFO within priority level
